Imagine a long web page with many sections (like a single HTML page). Could the web server send just that specific section (e.g., page.html#section7) first, and then the rest of the page later?
Sequence of flow:
1. From the beginning of the HTML document until the <body> tag
2. The HTML code for section 7
3. The HTML code for parts 1, 2, and 3
The browser must ensure that parts 1 through 6 are inserted above the seventh part on the web page.
Is this reasonable? Would it be useful?
I want to achieve the goal of rendering the linked part (#section7) as quickly as possible without reimplementing it with JavaScript or similar. I want a very long HTML document where the linked parts can still render quickly, and this can be achieved solely with HTML.
Content can be streamed like this, and then the browser will insert each <contents> element into the corresponding <div> element.
<div id="sec1"></div>
<div id="sec2"></div>
Wait
<div id="sec7">section 7…</div>
<contents for="sec1">section 1…</contents>
<contents for="sec2">section 2…</contents>
etc.
Although the streaming order is out of sequence, the browser will assemble the HTML document in order.
@user22 Actually, you can reorder the document content without using JS. However, if you want the server to do something, you can't use the hash part of the URL; instead, you need to use query string parameters to let the server know which part you want to see first. As for reordering the page content, you have the following options:
1. Use CSS
2. Use templates with slots
@user23 Correct. The issue is that the visual order (what the user sees) does not match the DOM order. If HTML could support out-of-order streaming, and the browser could still arrange the content in order within the DOM, it might be quite useful.
However, the slot method seems promising. I'll give it a try.
@user22 Oh, do you want the browser to automatically correct the DOM order?
@user23 Correct, that's exactly what I mean. The only reason for sending the 7th section first is to let the user see it as soon as possible. It would be great if this could be achieved without affecting the DOM order, so that the browser can ensure the final DOM order matches the visual order.
In other words, send the 7th section first, but the final result (DOM and visual effects) should be exactly the same as if all sections were sent in order.
@user22 @user33 Check out PHOOOS without JS: https://github.com/niutech/phooos
